ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical characteristics of the present method were compared with those of the previously reported CBQDs-based AA assay methods (Table 4
                        ). The detection methods have used the turn-on [36,77], turn-off [7,78], turn-off–on [6,32,34,35,37], and turn-on–off–on [31,33] mechanisms. Also, two colorimetric sensing methods [79,80] were considered in this comparison. The compared important parameters were linear dynamic range (LDR), LOD, repeatability, accuracy, and the types of analyzed samples. The present method exhibited LDR, LOD, RSD%, and recovery% equal to 0.3–11.5 µmol/L, 0.05 µmol/L, 2.3, and 99.2, respectively. In addition, the method applied to AA detection in tablets, lemon, and bell peppers. The results in Table 4 showed that the present method had exhibited a wider LDR [36,80], lower LOD [6,31,35,36,77,78,80], a broader range of the sample types that were analyzed [6,7,33–36,77–79], and suitable repeatability and accuracy [7,31,32,35–37,79] against the mentioned methods. Also, the present method used simple equipment and procedures. In addition, an essential advantage of the present method is the speed of analysis. The advantage is related to the intrinsic properties of FI setups. The sample throughput was 70 h−1 
                        [6,7,31–37,77–80]. Besides these advantages, the present AA assay method suffers a moderate drawback in selectivity. Phenolic compounds (as one of the essential radical scavenging chemicals) have serious interference effects, although they are not found considerably in common AA-containing samples.
